pulltitle: Add Mozilla Code of Conduct
pullsbody:
Fixes #185


As of January 1 2019, Mozilla requires that all GitHub projects include this [CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md](https://github.com/mozilla/repo-templates/blob/master/templates/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md) file in the project root. The file has two parts:

1. Required Text - All text under the headings *Community Participation Guidelines and How to Report*, are required, and should not be altered.
2. Optional Text - The Project Specific Etiquette heading provides a space to speak more specifically about ways people can work effectively and inclusively together. Some examples of those can be found on the [Firefox Debugger](https://github.com/devtools-html/debugger.html/blob/master/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md) project, and [Common Voice](https://github.com/mozilla/voice-web/blob/master/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md). (The optional part is commented out in the [raw template file](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mozilla/repo-templates/blob/master/templates/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md), and will not be visible until you modify and uncomment that part.)

If you have any questions about this file, or Code of Conduct policies and procedures, please see [Mozilla-GitHub-Standards](https://wiki.mozilla.org/GitHub/Repository_Requirements) or email Mozilla-GitHub-Standards+CoC@mozilla.com.

_(Message COC002)_
pull_repo_desc: Inferno Rules and Schemas for Tiles project
pull_commit_message:
Add Mozilla Code of Conduct file

Fixes #185.

_(Message COC002)_

pulltitle: Add a rule to produce the hustle marble
pullsbody:
This implements an automatic inferno rule to produce the Hustle marbles for hll.

## Change highlights

* Update the automatic rule "activity_stream_stats" so that it creates new tag(s) `incoming:activity_stream_user_counting:YYYY-mm-dd` in the "rule_cleanup" once it's completed.
* Add a new automatic rule (with custom map/reduce/combine functions) "activity_stream_user_counting" to generate Hustle marbles, the input tag is the output tag of rule "activity_stream_stats", i.e. these two rules will be running in lockstep.
* Current dimension columns are `date`, `release_channel`, `country_code`, and `version`, we can add more if needed.
* Haven't yet optimized the `MAX_BLOBS` of the new rule, an optimal value would lead to a better query performance.
* Still owe the repo some unit tests :)

## Try it out locally

```
# do this in hustle shell
>> bin/hustle
>> tab = Table.create('as_hlls', columns=['index string date', 'index trie16 release_channel', 'index trie16 version', 'index trie16 country_code', 'binary hll'], partition='date')

# in your system shell
>> ddfs chunk incoming:activity_stream:YYYY-mm-dd ./some_logs.json
>> inferno -i rules.activity_stream_stats
>> inferno -i rules.activity_stream_user_counting

# query it in hustle
>> bin/hustle
>>  from hustle.cardinality import h_cardinality as h_hll
>>  select(as_hlls.release_channel, as_hlls.version,  h_hll(as_hlls.hll), where=((as_hlls.date == '2017-11-14') & (as_hlls.country_code == 'US'))
```

@tspurway first scan?
pull_repo_desc: Inferno Rules and Schemas for Tiles project
pull_commit_message: Add a rule to produce the hustle marble

pulltitle: Add script to expire data on DDFS
pullsbody:
This script could be executed in a cronjob that automatically expires data on DDFS.

Based on the `source_tags` in the Infernyx automatic rules, it deletes all the tags that got created before a specific date. Eventually Disco can trigger a GC to handle them properly. Note that it won't touch other tags, like manually created ones as well as the result tags, those tags should be deleted separately. 

Example usage:
- to delete tags created 7 days ago

``` shell
$ python scripts/expire_ddfs_data.py -n 7
```
- dryrun: to show which tags will be delete for the above example

``` shell
$ python scripts/expire_ddfs_data.py -n 7 -d
```
pull_repo_desc: Inferno Rules and Schemas for Tiles project
pull_commit_message: Add script to expire data on DDFS

Example usage:

pulltitle: Add activity-stream keyset piggybacking on application logs
pullsbody:
This adds a new keyset `activity_stream_stats` in the `application_stats` rule. Still working in progress. But we can start reviewing the existing code.

A new Onyx endpoint has been added in [here](https://github.com/oyiptong/onyx/pull/36) to capture all the pings from the Activity Stream add-on. The `activity_stream_stats_daily` table will be added in Redshift shortly, tracked by this [bug](https://github.com/oyiptong/splice/issues/314).

Questions:
1. do we still need UA and Geo info for AS?
2. There is a maximum 'session_duration' currently set as 20 minutes. Do we want to filter the pings based on this value. If we do, what's the reasonable max duration?

pullsbody:
This adds a new keyset `activity_stream_stats` in the `application_stats` rule. Still working in progress. But we can start reviewing the existing code.

A new Onyx endpoint has been added in [here](https://github.com/oyiptong/onyx/pull/36) to capture all the pings from the Activity Stream add-on. The `activity_stream_stats_daily` table will be added in Redshift shortly, tracked by this [bug](https://github.com/oyiptong/splice/issues/314).

Questions:
1. do we still need UA and Geo info for AS?
2. There is a maximum 'session_duration' currently set as 20 minutes. Do we want to filter the pings based on this value. If we do, what's the reasonable max duration?

pulltitle: feature_ip_click_counter
pullsbody:
This is a 'fraud detector'.  It works by running an Inferno job daily (1am) on the previous day's click/impression stream data and counting excessively repetitive clicks from specific IP addresses.  

It uses datadog statsd events to report.

r? @oyiptong
pull_repo_desc: Inferno Rules and Schemas for Tiles project
pull_commit_message: adding an IP click counter Inferno rule to catch fraudulent (ie. repetitive) clicking above threshold.  The job runs daily and reports Events through datadog.statsd

xcat_to_csv.py  - translates python internal line format into csv line format
histogram.py - does a group by on csv formatted lines
computeZ.py - computes Z values for site co-occurrences
extract.sh - shell script to do it all

pulltitle: fix credentials references for uploading to redshift
pullsbody:
aws metadata iam credentials are sts tokens. you have to include the token with the credentials passed to redshift as described here: http://docs.aws.amazon.com/redshift/latest/dg/r_copy-temporary-security-credentials.html

for the upload to s3 portion, not specifying credentials means that boto will automatically use the iam role's credentials. not sure if this will work, but I think we should try it.

pull_commit_message: fix credentials references for uploading to redshift
